<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>burninjurycalc.com is written and reviewed by a small editorial team at The Click Lab. Burn-injury cases sit at the intersection of complex acute medicine, prolonged reconstructive surgery, and a damages framework with several burn-specific features (disfigurement as a separate damages category, life-care plans that span decades of iterative reconstruction, and PTSD-driven non-economic damages). Getting the content right means working from primary sources: American Burn Association (ABA) standards, the Lund-Browder chart and Rule of Nines references, published burn-life-care planning frameworks, leading appellate decisions on disfigurement and reconstructive-cost damages, and verdict and settlement databases tracking burn outcomes.</p>

  <h2>How we work</h2>
  <p>Every guide on this site follows the same workflow. A contributor drafts the article working from primary sources &mdash; ABA standards, peer-reviewed burn-medicine literature, life-care planning textbooks (King's, Deutsch &amp; Sawyer), state-specific catastrophic injury statutes and case law on disfigurement valuation, and burn-verdict tracker data. The editor reviews the draft for accuracy of citation, internal consistency of damages analysis, and whether the article actually answers a question a real reader (patient, family member, or attorney) would ask. The calculator team verifies any formulas or worked examples against published settlement distributions. The final piece is published with the reviewer's byline.</p>
  <p>We don't publish "thin" content. Every guide is intended to answer a specific question a non-lawyer reader might ask &mdash; what is the typical settlement range for a 25% TBSA hand burn, how is reconstructive surgery valued, what's the difference between hypertrophic and contracture scarring, what factors affect compensation &mdash; with enough specificity to be useful, while being honest about the limits of general informational content.</p>

  <h2>Contributors</h2>

  <h3>Cosmo Marchetti (CM) &mdash; Burn Injury Practice Lead</h3>
  <p><em>Paralegal &mdash; burn and catastrophic injury litigation.</em></p>
  <p>Cosmo has spent the last 12 years working at firms specializing in burn injuries and other catastrophic injury matters. He has supported attorneys on hundreds of burn cases ranging from restaurant-scald premises liability to defective-product fires (lithium battery, e-cigarette, gas grill) to industrial chemical and electrical burns. His hands-on experience covers medical-record analysis for burn-center admissions, life-care plan review for iterative reconstructive surgery, expert coordination for disfigurement valuation, and the specific procedural complexity of product-liability burn cases. Cosmo wrote the bulk of the compensation methodology content on this site and reviews every piece for technical accuracy against the underlying medical and legal sources. He cites ABA standards, the Lund-Browder chart, and the published burn-verdict trackers the way other writers cite primary literature. He is not a licensed attorney; his role on this site is editorial.</p>

  <h3>Iris Bowen (IB) &mdash; Contributing Writer, Medical Documentation &amp; Burn Care</h3>
  <p><em>Paralegal &mdash; medical records and burn-center experience.</em></p>
  <p>Iris focuses on the medical-evidence side of burn content. Before transitioning to paralegal work she spent several years in administrative roles at burn-center programs, where she developed deep familiarity with how burn admissions are documented, what records actually capture (and what they miss), and the cadence of reconstructive-surgery scheduling over the months and years following acute discharge. Iris writes the content explaining how depth and TBSA are documented, what categories of life-care needs typically dominate the cost projection, what scar evolution looks like over the first 2&ndash;5 years, and what medical questions a family should be asking their burn-center team. She has a granular sense of which medical and care-planning details actually move case valuation. She is not a licensed attorney or medical provider; her role is to make complex medical and care-planning concepts understandable.</p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cite the authority.</strong> Every rule we discuss is grounded in a specific source &mdash; ABA standards, the Lund-Browder chart or Rule of Nines, a state's catastrophic injury statute, an appellate opinion on disfigurement valuation, or peer-reviewed burn-medicine literature. When we describe a rule, we name the source.</li>
    <li><strong>No legal or medical advice.</strong> Everything on this site is general and informational. Burn-injury cases require evaluation by an experienced burn-injury attorney and care by burn-center specialists. We don't review individual cases or substitute for professional consultation.</li>
    <li><strong>No paid placements.</strong> We don't accept money, gifts, or other consideration to recommend law firms, attorneys, burn centers, or care providers. The only ads on the site are programmatic Google AdSense ads; we don't choose what runs.</li>
    <li><strong>Plain language first.</strong> Burn-injury terms (<em>TBSA</em>, <em>Lund-Browder</em>, <em>escharotomy</em>, <em>hypertrophic scarring</em>, <em>contracture release</em>, <em>split-thickness autograft</em>, <em>economic and non-economic damages</em>, <em>disfigurement valuation</em>) are defined where they're first used.</li>
    <li><strong>Worked examples.</strong> Abstract numbers without context are hard to apply. Most guides include at least one worked example with realistic burn facts and recovery analysis.</li>
    <li><strong>Sensitive to context.</strong> Burn-injury content reaches people in difficult circumstances &mdash; recently-burned patients, family members, parents of burned children. We aim for substantive content without being clinical, informative without being alarmist.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Sources we rely on</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>American Burn Association (ABA) standards</strong> &mdash; verified burn-center criteria, burn classification standards, and management guidelines.</li>
    <li><strong>The Lund-Browder chart</strong> &mdash; the more accurate TBSA estimation method used in major burn centers, particularly for children where body proportions differ from adults.</li>
    <li><strong>Life-care planning textbooks</strong> &mdash; King's <em>Life Care Planning</em>, Deutsch &amp; Sawyer's <em>Guide to Rehabilitation</em>, and the peer-reviewed life-care planning literature.</li>
    <li><strong>State catastrophic injury statutes and case law</strong> &mdash; appellate opinions on disfigurement damages, collateral source rules, and product-liability burn outcomes.</li>
    <li><strong>Verdict and settlement databases</strong> &mdash; VerdictSearch, Jury Verdict Research, and burn-specialty publications tracking outcomes by depth, TBSA, and cause.</li>
    <li><strong>Burn-medicine literature</strong> &mdash; peer-reviewed publications on burn prognosis, scar evolution, reconstructive sequencing, and PTSD in burn survivors.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Corrections</h2>
  <p>If you find an error &mdash; an outdated burn classification description, a calculator output that doesn't match the underlying formula, an incorrect statutory citation &mdash; please email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a> with the page URL and what's wrong. Verified corrections are typically made within a few business days. Material corrections are noted at the bottom of the affected page.</p>

  <h2>Reviewer disclosures</h2>
  <p>Our contributors are not licensed attorneys or medical providers. They are credentialed paralegals with substantive experience in burn-injury practice and life-care planning. Reviewing legal and medical content for accuracy is part of these professionals' skill sets and is not the same as giving legal or medical advice. Nothing on this site should be construed as legal or medical advice, and nothing here creates an attorney-client or treating-provider relationship.</p>

  <h2>Contact the editorial team</h2>
  <p>Editorial questions, citation suggestions, or interview requests: <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We respond within a few business days.</p>
</BaseLayout>
